element.label: Root
element.description: single root to ensure tree viewers like this

element.label: assay
element.description: An experiment carried out to test the effect of a perturbagen on a biological entity, measuring one or more readout facilitated by an assay design and assay type, and record the results one or more endpoint that quantifies or qualifies the extent of perturbation.

element.label: biology
element.description: A biological entity or process that is the presumed subject of the assay; may refer to a macromolecule whose activity is being regulated, or to a cell-biological process (e.g., neurite outgrowth).

element.label: assay component role
element.description: A role associated with an assay component.

element.label: assay measurement
element.description: An abstract concept to group multiple assay readouts and allow description of an assay that measures more than one effect of a perturbagen on the biological entity.

element.label: molecular target
element.description: A biological entity that has the role of target of an assay; usually a biological macromolecule that interacts with a perturbagen to produce the readout detected by the assay.

element.label: biological entity
element.description: A material entity of biological origin (e.g., protein, cell culture, tissue).

element.label: assay format
element.description: A concept of an assay based on the biological or chemical features of the assay components, including biochemical assays with purified protein, cell-based assays performed whole cells, and organism-based assays performed in an organism.

element.label: detection method type
element.description: A physical method (technology) used to measure one or more readout of the effect caused by a perturbagen in the assay.

element.label: biochemical format
element.description: An in vitro format used to measure the activity of a biological macromolecule, either purified protein or nucleic acid; most often a homogenous assay format, but can be heterogeneous if a solid phase (e.g. beads) is used to immobilize the macromolecule.

element.label: cell-based format
element.description: A heterogenous assay format that involves living cells of eukaryotic origin.

element.label: cell-free format
element.description: An in vitro format where biological material originates from cells, but does not use live cells nor purified macromolecules; most often a homogenous assay format, but can be heterogeneous if a solid phase (e.g. beads) is used to immobilize the components.

element.label: organism-based format
element.description: A heterogenous assay format that involves living organisms.

element.label: tissue-based format
element.description: A heterogenous assay format that involves tissue derived from a living organism.

element.label: nucleic-acid format
element.description: A format in which the perturbagen targets nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) to regulate its function.

element.label: protein format
element.description: A format in which the perturbagen targets a protein to regulate its function.

element.label: sub-cellular format
element.description: A format using sub-cellular organelles (but not individually purified proteins) obtained by cell lysis and fractionation (e.g., differential centrifugation).

element.label: whole-cell lysate format
element.description: A format using cells whose membranes have been ruptured (e.g., mechanically, osmotically) and whose lysate is used without separation techniques.

element.label: assay method
element.description: The underlying method (technology) and assay strategy used to determine the action of the perturbagen in the assay system.

element.label: assay biosafety level
element.description: A biosafety level is the level of biocontainment required to isolate hazardous biological agents in an enclosed facility. The levels of containment range from the lowest biosafety level of 1 to the highest at level 4.

element.label: assay condition
element.description: A set of optimization guidelines used to minimize the time and cost of assay implementation, while providing reliable assay performance.

element.label: assay footprint
element.description: This describes the physical format such as plate density in which an assay is performed, which is generally a microplate format, but can also be an array format.

element.label: assay readout content
element.description: This describes the throughput and information content generated. Categorizing multiplexed (i.e. multiple targets measured simultaneously) and multiparametric assays and high content (image-based) and regular (plate reader) assays.

element.label: incubation time
element.description: An interval of time between the addition of pertubagen, substrate, or cell modification, and the measurement of change using the detection method of the assay.

element.label: signal direction
element.description: It is the trend of measured readout signal, whether it increases or decreases in perturbagen treated wells, as compared to the untreated or carrier-treated wells in an assay.

element.label: unit of measurement
element.description: It is the inite magnitude of a physical quantity or of time. It has a quantity and a unit associated with it.

element.label: wavelength
element.description: For fluorescence measurements, it is the wavelength at which the fluorophore is excited and the wavelength at which it emits fluorescence. In the case of absorbance, it is the wavelength at which light is absorbed by a biological entity or a dye.

element.label: cell modification
element.description: This describes the type of alterations performed on the cell line, which include plasmid transfection, viral transduction, cell fusion, etc.

element.label: perturbagen delivery
element.description: A description of whether perturbagens are tested individually or as pooled mixtures.

element.label: assay panel
element.description: An abstract concept to group multiple assay instances and allow description of a group of assays that measure more than one effect of a perturbagen directed at prioritization by viewing the results together (e.g., a selectivity panel of assays for activity against each member of a family of related proteins).

element.label: assay stage
element.description: A description of the purpose of an assay within a project; relates to the order of assays in a screening campaign (e.g., a primary assay is performed first to identify hits, which are then confirmed in a confirmatory assay, after which secondary assays further prioritize confirmed hits).

element.label: confirmatory assay
element.description: An assay performed to confirm activity of perturbagens identified in a primary assay; may be performed as replicate measurements or as a concentration-response assay.

element.label: lead-optimization assay
element.description: An assay performed in the lead-optimization stage on a relatively small number of active perturbagens; typically a high-quality concentration-response assay.

element.label: primary assay
element.description: An assay performed (usually first in a campaign) to identify potentially biologically active pertubagens; usually performed at a single concentration with one or two measurements.

element.label: secondary assay
element.description: An assay performed following a confirmatory assay to confirm the biological activity a perturbagen using a different assay type or design; may address mode-of-action, toxicity, activity profile, and selectivity.

element.label: screening campaign
element.description: A concept to group multiple assay instances whose sequential performance is used to identify active pertubagens with a specific function and establish mode-of-action; usally progresses through primary assay, confirmatory assays, secondary assays, and lead-optimization assays.

element.label: curve-fit specification
element.description: A descripition of curve-fit parameters used to obtain an endpoint by fitting a single function across a range of measurements; contains information about curve-fit parameters, methods, properties (e.g., Hill coefficient), concentration range, and replicates.

element.label: normalization method
element.description: A description of a data normalization method (e.g., normalized percent distribution, Z-score, B-score) used to correct raw data for inference errors (i.e., false negatives and false positives), especially after testing at a single concentration or with a small number of replicates.

element.label: endpoint mode-of-action
element.description: A description of the qualitative effect of a perturbagen in an assay (e.g., inhibition, activation, cytotoxicity).

element.label: concentration endpoint
element.description: An endpoint expressed as a concentration at which a perturbagen mediates a ined response (e.g., IC50, EC50); always has one value in units of molar concentration.

element.label: biochemical constant endpoint
element.description: An endpoint used to express binding constants or enzyme kinetic constants reflecting interactions between ligands and macromolecules (e.g., Bmax, Kd).

element.label: response endpoint
element.description: An endpoint reporting the magnitude or relative magnitude of effect induced by a perturbagen; often expressed relative to control measurements.

element.label: temperature endpoint
element.description: An endpoint that reports a change in temperature as a measure of the extent of perturbation (e.g., Tm).

element.label: binding constant
element.description: This endpoint type describes the bonding affinity between two molecules at equilibrium, e.g., drug-receptor interaction.

element.label: enzyme kinetic constant
element.description: Describe kinetics of enzyme-catalyzed reactions. It includes the enzyme kinetic constants namely, Km and Vmax, which help to model the time course of disappearance of substrate and the production of product.

element.label: small-molecule collection source
element.description: A description of whether a small-molecule collection was purchased from a vendor or generated in an academic institution.

element.label: construct gene form
element.description: It describes whether the gene that is inserted in the construct is wild type or mutated, truncated, etc.

element.label: growth mode
element.description: This describes the growth mode of a cell line, whether it grows attached to the culture dish (adherent) or floating (suspension) in the culture medium or partially attached (mixed adherent and suspension).

element.label: culture serum
element.description: Cultured cells require serum or growth factors for growth by cell division. Each cell type is grown in a medium supplemented with a variable concentration of serum (up to 20%) which is optimized for its growth. Specialized sera include dextran charcoal treated serum, which lacks certain hormones, growth factors, etc, dialyzed serum, which lacks low molecular weight molecules (below 10,000 MW), such as glucose, amino acids, low molecular weight hormones, cytokines, etc. These sera are used in certain assays to avoid interference from the normal serum components. Most commonly, fetal bovine serum is used in cell culture, but other sera such as horse serum are also used.

element.label: culture medium
element.description: The liquid broth used to grow cells, which is optimized for each cell type and includes additives such as growth factors, buffers, amino acids, antibiotics, etc. This information can be obtained from ATCC or found in relevant publications.

element.label: endpoint assay
element.description: In this assay, change in activity is measured at one time point.

element.label: kinetic assay
element.description: In this assay, change in activity is measured at several time points over a period of time.

element.label: assay phase
element.description: It refers to whether all the assay components are in solution or some are in solid phase, which determines their ability to scatter light.

element.label: Bmax
element.description: It is the amount of drug required to saturate a population of receptors and a measure of the number of receptors present in the sample. It is derived from Scatchard plot of binding data. It is analogous to Vmax in enzyme kinetics. The units of Bmax include cpm, sites/cell or fmol/mg. http

element.label: Vmax
element.description: Vmax is ined as the maximum initial velocity of an enzyme catalyzed reaction under the given conditions, and it is measured in units of quantity of substrate transformed per unit time for a given concentration of enzyme.

element.label: area-under-curve
element.description: Area (e.g., integral) under a curve.

element.label: assay incubation time
element.description: An interval of time between the addition of pertubagen, substrate, or cell modification, and the measurement of change using the detection method of the assay.

element.label: assay panel ID
element.description: Assay panel IDs of assay panels (within a project) included in a screening campaign.

element.label: bi-directional
element.description: A trend in which the desired signal for perturbagens of interest can be either an increase or a decrease in the raw assay measurement.

element.label: calculated value
element.description: A readout in which the reported value is actually derived from raw values but in which the calculated value is typically reported by the instrument or is immediately used (e.g., temperature shift in a protein melting assay, ratio of luminescence values in a DualGlo assay, or a fluorescence polarization or anisotropy assay).

element.label: cell-culture component
element.description: Components of a specific medium in which a cell culture is prepared, which is optimized for its growth; includes medium additives such as serum, growth factors, buffers, amino acids, and antibiotics (this information may be obtained from ATCC or found in relevant publications).

element.label: Cmax
element.description: A maximal concentration achieved in a dosing experiment (maximum point of a concentration curve).

element.label: construct regulatory region
element.description: A name of a promoter or artificial regulatory element inserted upstream of a reporter gene in a DNA construct.

element.label: construct vector name
element.description: A name for a vector, an extrachromosomal, self-replicating DNA molecule that is used as a vehicle to deliver a DNA construct into cells, e.g., plasmid vector (pGEM-T, pBluescript), lentiviral vector, retroviral vector.

element.label: cps
element.description: Counts per second

element.label: frequency
element.description: A unit of measure for observations based on a number of events counted, including collection of photons by an instrument as in fluorescence or luminescence assays.

element.label: gain-of-signal
element.description: A trend in which the desired signal for perturbagens of interest is an increase in the raw assay measurement.

element.label: graphical calculation endpoint
element.description: An endpoint derived from calculus-based analysis of graphical measures.

element.label: Km
element.description: A Michaelis-Menten binding constant.

element.label: loss-of-signal
element.description: A trend in which the desired signal for perturbagens of interest is a decrease in the raw assay measurement.

element.label: macromolecule description
element.description: A long name for a gene or protein from a trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt).

element.label: macromolecule identifier
element.description: An external database unique identifier, such as an accession number, for a gene or protein from a trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt).

element.label: macromolecule identifier source
element.description: A trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt) of the gene or protein name.

element.label: macromolecule name
element.description: A short symbol or name for a gene or protein from a trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt).

element.label: measurement throughput
element.description: A description of the throughput qualities of measurements performed on each sample (i.e., perturbagen) in the instance; includes instance-specific information not intrinsic to the assay, such as number of replicates and number of sample concentrations tested.

element.label: measurement type
element.description: A description of whether a change in an assay is measured once at a fixed end-point, or over a period of time at several time points.

element.label: optical density
element.description: A concentration of suspensions as measured by the optical density, usually at 600 nM (typically used for cultures of microorganisms).

element.label: physical property endpoint
element.description: A measurement of an intrinsic property of a molecular entity.

element.label: PubChem CID
element.description: A compound identifier of a ined chemical structure, assigned by PubChem.

element.label: quality assessment
element.description: A description of commonly used statistical parameters to monitor assay quality, including Z and Z-prime factors; prior to starting a large screen, and after assay optimization and miniaturization, a pilot screen is typically performed to assess quality of an assay using these parameters.

element.label: result source
element.description: Assay instance IDs and assay readout IDs of assay instances and their assay readouts from which a result is derived.

element.label: RFU
element.description: Relative fluorescence units, a standard raw measurement for fluorescence-based assays, either direct fluorescence intensity (FI) measurements or energy transfer assays such as FRET.

element.label: RLU
element.description: Relative light units, a standard measurement unit for luminescence assays.

element.label: small-molecule format
element.description: An assay format with no biological component that is intended to measure the physical properties of a compound and not its effect on a biological system.

element.label: T1/2
element.description: An endpoint expressiong half-life.

element.label: X-fold dilution
element.description: A unit that is a multiple of some standard inition of a kit of solution (e.g., 0.5x TBE or 2X PBS).

element.label: mg/kg
element.description: millgrams per kilo - dose measure

element.label: dose
element.description: dose measure

instanceDescriptor.label: macromolecule description
instanceDescriptor.description: A long name for a gene or protein from a trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt).

instanceDescriptor.label: macromolecule identifier
instanceDescriptor.description: An external database unique identifier, such as an accession number, for a gene or protein from a trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt).

instanceDescriptor.label: macromolecule identifier source
instanceDescriptor.description: A trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt) of the gene or protein name.

instanceDescriptor.label: macromolecule name
instanceDescriptor.description: A short symbol or name for a gene or protein from a trusted international source (e.g., Entrez, UniProt).

instanceDescriptor.label: screening campaign
instanceDescriptor.description: A concept to group multiple assay instances whose sequential performance is used to identify active pertubagens with a specific function and establish mode-of-action; usally progresses through primary assay, confirmatory assays, secondary assays, and lead-optimization assays.

instanceDescriptor.label: assay panel ID
instanceDescriptor.description: Assay panel IDs of assay panels (within a project) included in a screening campaign.

instanceDescriptor.label: assay panel
instanceDescriptor.description: An abstract concept to group multiple assay instances and allow description of a group of assays that measure more than one effect of a perturbagen directed at prioritization by viewing the results together (e.g., a selectivity panel of assays for activity against each member of a family of related proteins).

laboratory.description: Singular root to ensure tree viewers work

unit.description: Singular root to ensure tree viewers work
A concentration of suspensions as measured by the optical density, usually at 600 nM (typically used for cultures of microorganisms).
A unit of measure for observations based on a number of events counted, including collection of photons by an instrument as in fluorescence or luminescence assays.
Relative fluorescence units, a standard raw measurement for fluorescence-based assays, either direct fluorescence intensity (FI) measurements or energy transfer assays such as FRET.
Relative light units, a standard measurement unit for luminescence assays.
